description.en:
The combinatory entropy for two types of complex polymer solutions has been calculated based on the Flory-Huggins theory. The combinatory entropy for polymer solution with polymer chains consisting of two kind of parts, rod and flexible parts is given by:
Delta Sf-r/R = Delta SF-H/R + {1 + beta - (1 - r(-1))Phi(2)} ln {1 - Phi(2)(1 - r(-1))/(beta+1)} - (r(-1) + beta) X Phi(2) ln {1 - (1 - r(-1))/(beta+1)}
where Delta SF-H/R = -Phi(1) ln Phi(1) - (Phi(2)/r) ln Phi(2) corresponds to the F-H theory, Phi(i) is the volume fraction of component (i), r is the number of segment per polymer, beta = a/c where a is the number of segments in the flexible part and c is the number of segments in the rod part, m is the number of repeated units in a chain and the unit consists of a flexible part and a rod part and m(a + c) = r - 1, Th(: combinatory entropy in the polymer solution where some solvent molecules interact with polymer segments strongly as 'solvation' is given by:
Delta S-solv/R = -(1/r) ln Phi(2) - {(1 + epsilon)(-1) - Phi(2)} ln {1 - Phi(2)(1 + epsilon)}
where epsilon is defined by epsilon = r(s)/r and r(s) is the number of solvents solvated per polymer. Correlation between Delta Sf-r in this work and those obtained by Guggenheim, Miller, Huggins and Kurata has been discussed and found that these are essentially the same. The partial molar entropy of solvent Delta S-1/R in polymer solution calculated in this work agreed with those obtained based on the experimental data in solution of polyisobutylene in n-pentane where Delta S-1/R is negative over low polymer concentration. (C) 1997 Elsevier Science B.V.
